[Pediatric childhood obsessive-compulsive disorder and/or tics, that
includes Tourette disorder, have been hypothesized as arising in a
subset of patients as a result of an autoimmune process that follows
group A beta-hemolytic streptococcal (GABHS) infections such as "strep
throat" and scarlet fever (Kurlan R, Johnson D, Kaplan EL; Tourette
Syndrome Study Group: Streptococcal infection and exacerbations of
childhood tics and obsessive-compulsive symptoms: a prospective
blinded cohort study. Pediatrics. 2008; 121(6): 1188-97;
http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/121/6/1188.long. Swedo
SE, Leonard HL, Garvey M, et al: Pediatric autoimmune neuropsychiatric
disorders associated with streptococcal infections: clinical
description of the first 50 cases [published correction appears in Am
J Psychiatry. 1998; 155: 578]. Am J Psychiatry. 1998; 155(2): 264-71;
http://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/article.aspx?articleid=172706).

The autoimmune process is thought to be analogous to that of Sydenham
chorea (a major neurologic manifestation of acute rheumatic fever).
The term PANDAS is the acronym for "Pediatric Autoimmune
Neuropsychiatric Disorder Associated with Streptococcal infections"
that has been applied to the disorder
(http://informahealthcare.com/doi/abs/10.1080/08916930500484757).

The news release, however, does not indicate the time line in which
the Tourette cases occurred and if any of the 6 cases had evidence of
GABHS infection.

LeRoy is a small town with a population of 7790 at the 2000 census in
Genesee County, Western New York State, United States
(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Roy_(town),_New_York). Genesee
County can be located on a map of New York State at
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Map_of_New_York_highlighting_Genesee_County.svg.
LeRoy can be located via the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of
New York at http://healthmap.org/r/1uEM. - Mod.ML]
